<title>Paper Scout Research Report - 2026-07-16</title>

<p>This run covers the July 14–15 paper drop and finds three unusually concrete threads around a single bet: <b>scalable robot learning is increasingly powered by synthetic training signals rather than more human data</b>. DenseReward generates physically realistic failures and dense progress rewards in simulation; TerraZero turns real-world map geometry into an unbounded procedural driving curriculum for zero-demonstration self-play; FlowWAM treats optical flow as a video-native action representation so a single pretrained video generator can both predict actions and render action-conditioned futures. Below each thread is investigated as a mechanism first and a set of numbers second.</p>

<callout emoji="✅" background-color="light-green">
  <p><b>Standout:</b> FlowWAM (arXiv 2607.13017) is the clearest seed for follow-up because its full policy code is public and the paper’s central architectural claims largely survive a code trace. DenseReward and TerraZero are conceptually strong but still paper-only releases.</p>
</callout>

<h1>Theme 1: Reward Learning from Synthesized Failures</h1>

<p>Reinforcement learning for manipulation has been stuck between sparse binary rewards that are easy to specify and dense rewards that require painstaking engineering. DenseReward asks whether a vision-language model can learn dense, per-timestep progress scores if it is trained on a dataset where failures are synthesized physically rather than relabeled from successes.</p>

<h2>DenseReward: Dense Reward Learning via Failure Synthesis for Robotic Manipulation</h2>
<p>Fang et al. (2026) · arXiv:2607.13033 · <a href="https://dense-reward.github.io/">project page</a></p>

<p>The core idea is a pipeline that decomposes pick-and-place manipulation into five phases—<b>Reach, Grasp, Lift, Move, Place</b>—and then induces six failure modes by perturbing a motion-planning pipeline built on GraspNet and CuRobo. The failures are physical, not counterfactual: collision avoidance is disabled for <i>Collision</i>; the grasp target is offset for <i>Miss</i>; rotation noise is injected during Move for <i>Fall</i>; Gaussian joint noise is added for <i>Smooth</i>; a collision is followed by replanning for <i>Recover</i>; and <i>Success</i> is unperturbed. Validity checks at phase boundaries filter physically implausible episodes.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:densereward:overview]]</p>

<p>The reward model itself is a Qwen3-VL-4B-Instruct fine-tuned with LoRA rank 16. It takes a language instruction, the current RGB frame, and <b>two historical frames</b> and outputs a scalar <latex>r_t \in [0,1]</latex> rounded to three decimals. The historical-frame ablation is telling: MAE drops from 0.096 (no history) to 0.088 (one frame) to 0.081 (two frames), then rises slightly to 0.086 with three frames—more context introduces noise.</p>

<p>What makes the reward signal different from prior work is that it is <b>dense and failure-aware</b>. Success trajectories rise monotonically; collision/miss/fall trajectories rise to the failure event and then decay, preserving partial-progress information; recover trajectories dip and resume. The paper does not give a closed-form reward formula, so I reconstructed the shapes from the qualitative rules and the result is shown below.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:densereward:curves]]</p>

<p>On the authors’ internal benchmark DenseReward reports MAE 0.081, well below RoboReward-8B (0.230) and zero-shot VLMs such as Qwen3-VL-4B (0.289). The MPC experiment is small but clean: 28 candidate actions per step are scored by the reward model, and DenseReward achieves the lowest average end-effector-to-object distance (0.229 vs. 0.267 for RoboReward-4B). The real-world DSRL result is the most eye-catching in a narrow sense: on a Franka arm, adding DenseReward improves success from 40% to 80% on “stack the cups” and from 30% to 70% on “put ball in basket,” with only ~10–20 real-world rollouts each.</p>

<p>The biggest caveat is reproducibility. As of this run the project-page “Code” and “Dataset” buttons are <code>href="#"</code> placeholders with HTML comments reading <code>&lt;!-- TODO: fill in arXiv / code / dataset URLs when available --&gt;</code>. The dense-reward GitHub organization only hosts the website repo. So the strong MAE and RL numbers cannot be independently checked, and the benchmark is author-constructed. Compared to RoboReward, which relabels successful demos to create negatives and predicts trajectory-level rewards, DenseReward is genuinely different: it synthesizes physically realistic failure trajectories and predicts per-timestep progress. The idea is clean; the artifact release is not.</p>

<h1>Theme 2: Driving Simulation for Zero-Demonstration Self-Play</h1>

<p>Closed-loop driving policies are usually trained on logged human trajectories or inside slow, feature-rich simulators. TerraZero argues you can have speed, fidelity, and zero demonstrations at the same time by building a fast C simulator and procedurally generating every scenario from real map geometry.</p>

<h2>TerraZero: Procedural Driving Simulation for Zero-Demonstration Self-Play at Scale</h2>
<p>Wu, Rangesh et al. (2026) · arXiv:2607.13028 · <a href="https://terra-applied.github.io/TerraZero">project page</a></p>

<p>TerraZero is a vectorized object-level driving simulator and PPO training stack from Applied Intuition. The engineering split is deliberate: a C simulation engine runs dynamics, observation construction, reward computation, and traffic-light state machines on the CPU, while PyTorch policy/value networks and PPO updates run on the GPU. The two communicate over a <b>zero-copy path</b>: shared numpy buffers are reinterpreted as fp16/bf16 tensors. The reported throughput is 560K agent-steps/sec on a consumer GPU, 1.30M on a single server GPU, and 2.80M on an 8-GPU node.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:terrazero:overview]]</p>

<p>The procedural generator treats logged data <b>only as map geometry</b>. It pulls maps from Waymo Open Motion, nuPlan (Las Vegas, Boston, Pittsburgh, Singapore), and five CARLA towns, then randomizes initialization, goals, agent dimensions, kinematic coefficients, reward weights, signal controllers (NEMA, Christmas, round-robin), and a mix of rule-based NPCs: IDM/PDM vehicles, parked/crashed vehicles, construction zones, ORCA pedestrians, and jaywalkers. The kinematic coefficients <latex>(c_{\text{throttle}}, c_{\text{steer}}, c_{\text{acc}}, c_{\text{vel}})</latex> are sampled per agent in <latex>[0.5, 1.5]</latex> and exposed in the observation, so one network learns to adapt online.</p>

<p>The training recipe is PPO with GAE, V-trace off-policy corrections, PopArt value normalization, prioritized advantage sampling, and synchronized normalization statistics across DDP/Ray ranks. Notably, the authors trade sample efficiency for compute efficiency: they discard low-advantage segments and rely on aggressive off-policy correction rather than on-policy data. The planner is a 3.5M-parameter MLP; the sim agent is a 6.7M-parameter heterogeneous network. Both use ego + Deep Sets encoders over partners, road, and traffic entities. Every reported policy trains from scratch with random initialization—no human demonstrations, no imitation, no logged trajectories, no fallback planner at inference.</p>

