<p>The SPACeR comparison is the sharpest framing. SPACeR, from the same group, anchors self-play to a pretrained tokenized reference model and leads on VRU realism; TerraZero shows you can approach similar vehicle realism without that reference policy at all. The cross-dataset transfer is also striking: a policy trained only on right-hand-traffic cities generalizes to left-hand-traffic Singapore, and CARLA-trained policies perform on par with those trained on hundreds of thousands of real scenarios.</p>

<p>But like DenseReward, TerraZero has no public source code, model weights, or terrabin scenario converters. The GitHub repos are project-page mirrors. The relationship to the later TerraTransfer paper confirms the simulator is a real internal codebase—TerraTransfer explicitly says it uses “our vectorized simulator” TerraZero for Phase 1 self-play—but external reproducibility is currently zero. The 1.3M SPS claim is physically plausible but unverified.</p>

<h1>Theme 3: Optical Flow as a Unified Action Representation</h1>

<p>World Action Models (WAMs) reuse pretrained video generators for both policy and world modeling, but the action representation has remained awkward: numerical tokens are embodiment-specific, learned latent actions are abstract, and image-space conditions are usually static “where” cues rather than “how” motion cues. FlowWAM proposes optical flow as the action modality.</p>

<h2>FlowWAM: Optical Flow as a Unified Action Representation for World Action Models</h2>
<p>Chen et al. (2026) · arXiv:2607.13017 · <a href="https://flow-wam.github.io">project page</a> · <a href="https://github.com/YixiangChen515/FlowWAM">code (policy)</a> · <a href="https://github.com/YixiangChen515/FlowWAM_WorldArena">code (world model)</a></p>

<p>The key observation is that optical flow is already a video: a per-pixel displacement field <latex>\mathbf{f}_t \in \mathbb{R}^{H \times W \times 2}</latex> can be mapped to an RGB image with an HSV color-wheel encoding,</p>

<p><latex>\text{H} = \frac{\operatorname{atan2}(v,u) + \pi}{2\pi}, \quad \text{S} = \frac{\|\mathbf{f}_t\|}{m}, \quad \text{V} = 1,</latex></p>

<p>where <latex>m</latex> is a magnitude cap. Because the resulting <latex>F_t</latex> has the same format as an RGB frame, it can be encoded by the same VAE and processed by the same diffusion transformer as the visual stream. FlowWAM builds on Wan2.2-TI2V-5B. The only stream-specific parameters are separate patch embeddings and heads for RGB and flow, plus a small learnable <code>stream_embed</code> token so the shared blocks can tell the modalities apart.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:flowwam:overview]]</p>

<p>Inside each DiT block the RGB and flow tokens are concatenated for joint self-attention, then split back to their respective streams. This lets the model do two things with one architecture:</p>

<ul>
  <li><b>Policy mode:</b> both RGB and flow latents are noised and jointly denoised; the generated flow plan is decoded into actions by an <b>action expert</b>.</li>
  <li><b>World-model mode:</b> the flow latents are set to the clean VAE encoding of a desired motion trajectory and held fixed; only the RGB latents are denoised.</li>
</ul>

<p>The action expert is a ~780M-parameter transformer that cross-attends to per-layer hidden states of the video DiT, conditions on the current proprioceptive state, and predicts a flow-matching velocity for an N-step action chunk. A neat train/test alignment trick: during training the latents fed to the video DiT are noised with probability 0.5 and the noise level is passed to the action expert as an auxiliary embedding, matching the imperfect generated latents it sees at inference.</p>

<p>On RoboTwin 2.0 FlowWAM reports 92.94% success under the Clean setting and 92.14% under Random, ahead of <latex>\pi_{0.5}</latex>, X-VLA, Motus, GigaWorld-Policy, X-WAM, and Fast-WAM. Pretraining on action-unlabeled human egocentric video (EgoDex) gives a larger gain under Random than Clean, which is the expected signature of visual-robustness transfer. On WorldArena it reports EWMScore 63.71, with the largest margin on Trajectory Accuracy.</p>

<p>The code trace supports most of the paper’s claims. The HSV codec is reversible and implemented in <code>reversible_flow_codec.py</code>; my pure-numpy probe gives ~0.001 px round-trip error for meaningful magnitudes. The dual-stream architecture, joint attention, action expert, and noise mixing are all present. But two caveats emerged:</p>

<ol>
  <li>The WorldArena repo omits the learnable <code>stream_embed</code> described in Appendix A.1, so the released world-model code deviates from the paper.</li>
  <li>The WorldArena inference script loads an external <b>SeedVR stage-2 refiner</b> by default, so the 63.71 EWMScore is not produced by the dual-stream model alone.</li>
  <li>The EgoDex action-unlabeled pretraining stage is described but <b>not released</b>; the only “stage 1” checkpoint in the WorldArena repo is trained on RoboTwin.</li>
</ol>

<p>These are manageable caveats for an unusually complete release. The genuine novelty is architectural: optical flow is not an auxiliary target or planning intermediate, but a full video stream that is generated for policy and conditioned on for world modeling inside the same pretrained DiT.</p>

