<h1>Cross-Cutting Observations</h1>

<p><b>Synthetic signals are the shared bet.</b> All three deep threads generate their own training signal instead of collecting more human data: DenseReward synthesizes failures, TerraZero synthesizes scenarios, FlowWAM synthesizes motion plans as flow videos. This is a coherent shift in the field’s research direction.</p>

<p><b>Code availability is the main differentiator.</b> FlowWAM ships full policy and world-model repositories; DenseReward and TerraZero are paper-only releases with placeholder project pages. That does not make the latter wrong, but it does make their strong quantitative claims provisional.</p>

<p><b>What remains uncertain.</b> For DenseReward, the actual reward formula and the independence of the benchmark are unknown. For TerraZero, throughput and the exact training stability recipe are unverified. For FlowWAM, the unreleased EgoDex pretraining stage and the external SeedVR refiner mean the scalability and WorldArena numbers need closer scrutiny than the RoboTwin numbers.</p>

<p><b>What to build next.</b> The most buildable idea is FlowWAM’s flow-as-action representation: it is concrete, code is available, and the same representation can be tested on new robots by swapping the action expert. The most important open question is whether the DenseReward failure-synthesis recipe transfers to non-pick-place tasks such as tool use and deformable-object manipulation.</p>
